# PowerShell Integration Guide

This project can be integrated with PowerShell to provide a global `pyproject` command.

## Two Integration Options

### Option 1: Use Virtual Environment

Add this function to your PowerShell profile to use the script with its virtual environment:

```powershell
function pyproject {
    param([Parameter(ValueFromRemainingArguments=$true)]$params)
    
    # Get the full path to the script directory and script
    $scriptDir = "C:\Users\chris\.myAiBS\system-tools\project-manager-cli"
    $scriptPath = Join-Path $scriptDir "pyproject.py"
    
    # Path to Python in the virtual environment
    $venvPython = Join-Path $scriptDir ".venv\Scripts\python.exe"
    
    # Call the Python script with the venv Python
    if ($params) {
        & $venvPython $scriptPath $params
    } else {
        & $venvPython $scriptPath
    }
}
```

### Option 2: Use PyInstaller Executable

For a standalone executable without dependency issues:

1. The project can be compiled to an executable with [pyproject.spec](mdc:pyproject.spec)
2. The executable is located in the [dist](mdc:dist) directory
3. PowerShell integration then uses the executable directly

```powershell
function pyproject {
    param([Parameter(ValueFromRemainingArguments=$true)]$params)
    
    # Path to the executable
    $exePath = "C:\Users\chris\.myAiBS\system-tools\project-manager-cli\dist\pyproject.exe"
    
    # Call the executable
    if ($params) {
        & $exePath $params
    } else {
        & $exePath
    }
}
```
